    "individual_blog_ehRj94": {
      "type": "individual-blog",
      "blocks": {
        "rich_text_k8xgxP": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Heading",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>An <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/engagement-rings\" title=\"Engagement Rings\">Engagement Ring</a> is one of the most meaningful pieces of jewelry you'll ever wear. But once that dazzling ring is yours, a practical question often follows: which hand should you wear it on? The answer isn't as simple as you might think - it’s shaped by tradition, culture, and even personal preference.</p><p>Let’s explore the different customs around the world and what might guide your own decision.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_iAAAmi": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Western Tradition: Left Hand Love",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>The Western Tradition: Left Hand Love</h2>",
            "custom_id": "western",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_j6gWNE": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Which_Hand_Should_You_Wear_Your_Engagement_Ring_On_Tradition_Culture_Explained_1st_Inside_Image_600_X_500.jpg",
            "text": "<p>In many Western countries - the United States, Canada, the UK, and much of Europe, the Engagement Ring is traditionally worn on the fourth fing<em>er of </em>the<em> </em>left hand. This finger is often called the “ring finger,” and the tradition dates back to ancient Rome. Romans believed that a vein, the <em>vena amoris</em> or “vein of love,” ran directly from this finger to the heart, symbolizing an unbroken connection between love and life.</p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "medium",
            "show_products": true,
            "products": [
              "0-12ct-round-diamond-channel-eternity-band",
              "0-150ct-half-eternity-round-diamond-band"
            ]
          }
        },
        "rich_text_G6iX9P": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Today, even though we know the anatomy isn’t quite that romantic (no such vein exists), the tradition has endured. For most brides and grooms in these countries, the engagement ring stays on the left hand both before and after marriage, typically joined by the wedding band on the same finger.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_dVDWnz": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Right-Hand Rings: The Global Perspective",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Right-Hand Rings: The Global Perspective</h2>",
            "custom_id": "right",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_nMT9Xb": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "name": "Image with Text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Which_Hand_Should_You_Wear_Your_Engagement_Ring_On_Tradition_Culture_Explained_2nd_Inside_Image_600_X_500.jpg",
            "text": "<p>While many Western countries favor the left hand for Engagement Rings, several Eastern cultures such as India, Russia and parts of the Middle East traditionally wear them on the right-hand ring finger. This preference is often tied to local customs and beliefs. </p><ul><li>In India, for instance, the right hand is considered more auspicious and symbolically stronger. </li><li>In Russia, wearing a ring on the right hand is thought to attract good luck and prosperity, reflecting cultural values around fortune and fidelity. </li></ul>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": false,
            "custom_id": "",
            "image_size_option": "medium",
            "show_products": true,
            "products": [
              "0-318ct-round-toi-et-moi-ring",
              "0-525ct-half-eternity-prong-diamond-band"
            ]
          }
        },
        "rich_text_P3WJVU": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<ul><li>In Orthodox Christian traditions, the right hand holds particular spiritual significance.</li><li>In Jewish tradition, it's also common to place the <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/wedding-rings\" title=\"Wedding Rings\">Wedding Ring</a> on the right hand during the ceremony, although many may later switch it to the left for daily wear.</li></ul>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_XfEW68": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Cultural Shifts and Personal Choice",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Cultural Shifts and Personal Choice</h2><p>What’s interesting is that, as the world becomes more interconnected, these traditions are increasingly blending. While many still follow the practices of their culture or family, others base their choice on personal style, comfort, or practicality. Since the dominant hand is typically more active in daily tasks, many people prefer wearing their engagement ring on the non-dominant hand to minimize wear and tear and make everyday activities easier.</p><p>In some same-sex marriages, partners may also opt for different traditions that reflect their own stories or identities, which further diversifies how and where engagement rings are worn.</p>",
            "custom_id": "culture",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_MgP7HE": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Engagement Ring and Wedding Band",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Engagement Ring and Wedding Bands: How Do They Stack?</h2><p>Another common question is what happens when the wedding band comes into the picture. In Western traditions, it’s typical to wear the wedding band closer to the heart, meaning the wedding band is placed first on the finger, followed by the Engagement Ring. Some people switch the Engagement Ring to the right hand for the Wedding Ceremony and then move it back afterward.</p><p>In other traditions, the two rings may be worn on different hands altogether, or sometimes only a wedding band is worn without an Engagement Ring.</p>",
            "custom_id": "bands",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_yLdr3L": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Conclusion",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Modern Takes: There’s No Wrong Way</h2><p>As Engagement Rings become more personal and unique, so do the ways we wear them. Today, it’s not uncommon to see rings worn as <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/pendant-necklaces\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Pendant Necklace\">pendant necklaces</a>, stacked with other meaningful bands, or designed in creative ways that break traditional molds.</p><p>The truth is, while traditions can provide beautiful meaning and connection to culture, your Engagement Ring is a symbol of your love story. Whether you follow ancient tradition, your family’s customs, or carve your own path, the most important thing is whether it feels right for you.</p><p>At <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Lucira Jewelry\">Lucira Jewelry</a>, we celebrate every love story, every tradition, and every personal choice. No matter how or where you wear your ring, let it be a reflection of your unique journey, shining with the brilliance and responsibility of Lab Grown Diamonds.</p>",
            "custom_id": "modern",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        }
      },
